subSubSection.paragraph:
DIAGNOSIS: The male of 

O. gigabulbus

is recognized by the very large palpal bul (
Figs. 320
, 
327
) and the embolus with a subapical knob (
Fig. 352
), in combination with the shape of the modified setae on the labium (
Fig. 338
). The female is characterized by the genitalic region with a stout, tube-shaped AUS with two knob-like lateral protrusions in front (
Fig. 332
).
